{
  "What is the purpose of a data table in science?": "",
  "To organize collected information in rows and columns for easy reading": "",
  "To replace graphs entirely so that no graphing is ever needed": "",
  "To display the hypothesis and conclusion of an experiment only": "",
  "To show only the final answer without including any raw data values": "",
  "A data table organizes information into rows and columns so scientists can easily record, read, and compare measurements. Well-organized data tables are essential for accurate analysis.": "",
  "What should be included in the column headers of a data table?": "",
  "Only numbers without any labels or descriptions": "",
  "The variable name and its units of measurement": "",
  "Only the scientist's name and the date of testing": "",
  "The conclusion of the experiment and hypothesis": "",
  "Column headers should include the variable name and its units (for example, 'Time (seconds)' or 'Mass (grams)'). This tells readers exactly what each column of data represents.": "",
  "How do you calculate the mean (average) of a set of data?": "",
  "Subtract the smallest value from the largest value in the set": "",
  "Add all values together and divide by the number of values": "",
  "Find the value that appears most often in the entire data set": "",
  "Arrange the values in order and pick the one in the middle": "",
  "To find the mean, add all the values and divide by the total number of values. For example, the mean of 4, 6, and 8 is (4 + 6 + 8) ÷ 3 = 6.": "",
  "What is the range of a data set?": "",
  "The value that appears most frequently in the data": "",
  "The difference between the largest and smallest values": "",
  "The middle value when data is arranged in order": "",
  "The sum of all values divided by the total count": "",
  "The range is calculated by subtracting the smallest value from the largest. For example, if your data is 3, 7, 9, 12, 15, then the range is 15 − 3 = 12. Range shows the spread of your data.": "",
  "A student records these test scores: 85, 90, 78, 92, 85. What is the mode?": "",
  "90": "",
  "86": "",
  "85": "",
  "78": "",
  "The mode is the value that appears most frequently. In this data set, 85 appears twice while all other values appear only once, making 85 the mode.": "",
  "What is the median of the data set: 3, 7, 9, 12, 15?": "",
  "7": "",
  "12": "",
  "9": "",
  "15": "",
  "The median is the middle value when data is arranged in order. In the set 3, 7, 9, 12, 15, the middle value is 9 (with two values below and two above).": "",
  "Where should the independent variable go in a data table?": "",
  "In the last column on the right side of the table": "",
  "In the first column on the left side of the table": "",
  "In the title row at the very top of the data table": "",
  "It should not be included in the data table at all": "",
  "By convention, the independent variable is placed in the first (leftmost) column of a data table. The dependent variable and any calculated values go in the columns to the right.": "",
  "A student records the following masses: 12.3 g, 12.5 g, 12.4 g, 12.3 g, 12.5 g. What is the mean?": "",
  "12.3 g": "",
  "12.5 g": "",
  "12.4 g": "",
  "12.6 g": "",
  "Add all values: 12.3 + 12.5 + 12.4 + 12.3 + 12.5 = 62.0. Divide by 5: 62.0 ÷ 5 = 12.4 g. The mean mass is 12.4 grams.": "",
  "Why should a data table have a descriptive title?": "",
  "So readers know what data the table contains and what experiment it relates to": "",
  "To make the table look more decorative and visually appealing on the page": "",
  "Because tables without titles will cause errors in all calculations performed": "",
  "So the teacher knows which student submitted the data table for grading": "",
  "A descriptive title tells the reader what data is contained in the table and what experiment it came from. Without a title, the data lacks context and is much harder to interpret correctly.": "",
  "What is the range of the data set: 14, 22, 18, 30, 25?": "",
  "22": "",
  "16": "",
  "18": "",
  "30": "",
  "The range is the largest value minus the smallest value: 30 − 14 = 16. This tells us the data spans 16 units from lowest to highest.": "",
  "What is the mean (average) in data analysis?": "",
  "The sum of all data values divided by the total number of values in the set": "",
  "The middle number when all values are arranged from smallest to largest": "",
  "The most frequently occurring value in an entire collected data set": "",
  "The difference between the highest and lowest values in a data set": "",
  "The mean is calculated by adding all data values together and dividing by how many values there are. It gives a central value that represents the typical measurement in the data set.": "",
  "What is the median in a data set?": "",
  "The average of the highest and lowest values in the data": "",
  "The middle value when all numbers are arranged in order": "",
  "The value that appears the most times in a data set": "",
  "The total of all values divided by their count in the set": "",
  "The median is found by arranging all values in order and selecting the middle one. If there is an even number of values, the median is the average of the two middle values.": "",
  "What is the mode of a data set?": "",
  "The value that occurs most frequently in the data set": "",
  "The average calculated by adding and dividing all data values": "",
  "The middle value found after arranging data in numerical order": "",
  "The difference between the maximum and minimum data values": "",
  "The mode is the value that appears most often. A data set can have one mode, more than one mode (if multiple values tie for most frequent), or no mode at all (if all values appear the same number of times).": "",
  "What does 'qualitative data' mean?": "",
  "Data described with words that relate to qualities like color, shape, or texture": "",
  "Data that can be measured with numbers and recorded using specific units": "",
  "Data that has been verified and confirmed by multiple scientists in the field": "",
  "Data that is collected only from controlled experiments in laboratory settings": "",
  "Qualitative data describes qualities or characteristics that cannot be measured with numbers, such as color (red), texture (smooth), smell (sweet), or shape (round).": "",
  "What does 'quantitative data' mean?": "",
  "Data that describes qualities using words such as color and texture": "",
  "Data that can be measured and expressed using numbers and units": "",
  "Data that only comes from surveys and questionnaires given to people": "",
  "Data that changes constantly and cannot be recorded in any data table": "",
  "Quantitative data is numerical and can be measured, such as height (152 cm), mass (45 kg), temperature (22°C), or time (30 seconds). Think 'quantity' = numbers.": "",
  "What does 'data analysis' mean?": "",
  "The process of examining data to find patterns, trends, and relationships": "",
  "The process of collecting data from an experiment before any calculations": "",
  "The step of writing a hypothesis before conducting any experiment tests": "",
  "The process of designing the experimental procedure and gathering tools": "",
  "Data analysis is the process of examining collected data to identify patterns, calculate statistics (mean, median, range), create graphs, and draw conclusions about the experiment's results.": "",
  "What does 'significant figures' mean in data recording?": "",
  "The digits in a measurement that are known with certainty plus one estimated digit": "",
  "The total number of decimal places written after the decimal point in a value": "",
  "Only the digits that appear before the decimal point in a measured value": "",
  "The largest and smallest values recorded in a complete data set overall": "",
  "Significant figures include all digits that are known with certainty from a measurement, plus one final estimated digit. They communicate the precision of a measurement.": "",
  "What is an 'anomaly' in a data set?": "",
  "A data point that is very close to the mean value of the data set": "",
  "An unusual result that does not fit the pattern of the rest of the data": "",
  "The most common measurement recorded during the experimental trials": "",
  "The average of the first and last values in the entire collected data set": "",
  "An anomaly (or outlier) is a data point that deviates significantly from the overall pattern. It may result from a measurement error, equipment malfunction, or unusual experimental condition.": "",
  "What does 'precision' mean in data collection?": "",
  "How close repeated measurements are to one another when taken multiple times": "",
  "How close a measured value is to the actual or accepted true value overall": "",
  "How many data points are collected during a single trial of an experiment": "",
  "How quickly the scientist is able to record the data values during tests": "",
  "Precision describes how close repeated measurements are to each other. If you measure something five times and get 10.2, 10.3, 10.2, 10.3, 10.2, your measurements are very precise.": "",
  "What does 'accuracy' mean in data collection?": "",
  "How close repeated measurements are to each other when taken multiple times": "",
  "How close a measured value is to the true or accepted value of that quantity": "",
  "How many digits are used to express a measurement in a data table entry": "",
  "How many trials the scientist performed during the course of the experiment": "",
  "Accuracy describes how close a measurement is to the true or accepted value. A measurement can be precise (consistent) but not accurate (close to the true value), or vice versa.": "",
  "A student measures the growth of plants over 5 weeks and records: 2 cm, 4 cm, 6 cm, 8 cm, 10 cm. What is the average growth per week?": "",
  "4 cm per week": "",
  "6 cm per week": "",
  "8 cm per week": "",
  "5 cm per week": "",
  "Calculate the mean: (2 + 4 + 6 + 8 + 10) ÷ 5 = 30 ÷ 5 = 6 cm. The average growth per week is 6 cm.": "",
  "A lab group records the time it takes a ball to roll down a ramp in 5 trials: 2.3 s, 2.5 s, 2.4 s, 5.1 s, 2.4 s. Which value is likely an anomaly?": "",
  "2.3 seconds": "",
  "2.5 seconds": "",
  "5.1 seconds": "",
  "2.4 seconds": "",
  "The value 5.1 seconds is much higher than the other four values, which cluster around 2.3–2.5 seconds. This makes it a likely anomaly (outlier), possibly caused by the ball being obstructed or a timing error.": "",
  "A student records the number of sit-ups done by classmates: 15, 22, 18, 20, 22, 17, 22, 19. Her teacher asks for the mode. What should she report?": "",
  "19.4 sit-ups": "",
  "22 sit-ups": "",
  "19 sit-ups": "",
  "18 sit-ups": "",
  "The mode is the most frequently occurring value. The number 22 appears three times, more than any other value, making it the mode of this data set.": "",
  "A scientist measures the temperature of a solution every 10 minutes: 25°C, 30°C, 35°C, 40°C, 45°C. She notices the data shows a pattern. What pattern does the data show?": "",
  "The temperature increases by 5°C every 10 minutes at a constant rate": "",
  "The temperature decreases by 5°C every 10 minutes at a constant rate": "",
  "The temperature stays the same and does not change at all over time": "",
  "The temperature changes randomly with no predictable pattern at all": "",
  "The data shows a consistent increase of 5°C every 10 minutes (25→30→35→40→45). This is a linear pattern — the temperature rises at a steady, constant rate.": "",
  "A student observes a rock and writes: 'The rock is gray, rough, and has shiny flecks.' What type of data is this?": "",
  "Quantitative data based on numerical measurements": "",
  "Qualitative data based on observed qualities and descriptions": "",
  "Experimental data recorded from a controlled laboratory test": "",
  "Calculated data derived from mathematical formulas and equations": "",
  "This is qualitative data because it describes qualities (color, texture, appearance) using words rather than numbers. Quantitative data would include measurements like 'The rock has a mass of 45 grams.'": "",
  "A student measures the length of a pencil five times: 18.2 cm, 18.3 cm, 18.2 cm, 18.2 cm, 18.3 cm. The actual length is 19.0 cm. Are the measurements precise, accurate, or both?": "",
  "Both precise and accurate because the values are consistent and correct": "",
  "Accurate but not precise because they are close to the true value only": "",
  "Precise but not accurate because they are consistent but far from the true value": "",
  "Neither precise nor accurate because the values are all different from each other": "",
  "The measurements are precise because they are very close to each other (18.2–18.3 cm). However, they are not accurate because they are all far from the true value of 19.0 cm.": "",
  "A class collects data on how many books each student read last month: 2, 3, 1, 4, 2, 3, 2, 5, 2, 3. The teacher asks for the median. What is it?": "",
  "3 books": "",
  "2 books": "",
  "2.5 books": "",
  "2.7 books": "",
  "First arrange in order: 1, 2, 2, 2, 2, 3, 3, 3, 4, 5. With 10 values, the median is the average of the 5th and 6th values: (2 + 3) ÷ 2 = 2.5 books.": "",
  "A scientist collects temperature data for a week but notices one day's reading is 150°C when all other days are between 20°C and 25°C. What should she do with this unusual reading?": "",
  "Include it without question because all data should always be included": "",
  "Investigate the reading for possible errors before deciding to include it or not": "",
  "Change it to 25°C so that it fits with the rest of the data in the set": "",
  "Delete all data from the week and restart the entire data collection process": "",
  "The 150°C reading is likely an error (perhaps the thermometer malfunctioned or was misread). The scientist should investigate the cause. If it was a confirmed error, it can be noted and excluded from analysis.": "",
  "A student's data table has no units in the column headers. Her temperatures read 22, 25, 28, 31. A classmate asks if those are in Celsius or Fahrenheit. Why does the missing information matter?": "",
  "It does not matter because temperature is always measured in Celsius in science": "",
  "Without units, the data cannot be properly interpreted or compared with other data": "",
  "It only matters if the student plans to convert the temperature to another unit": "",
  "Missing units automatically make all the numerical values recorded incorrect": "",
  "Without units, the data is ambiguous. 22°C and 22°F are very different temperatures (22°C ≈ 72°F). Units are essential for proper interpretation, comparison, and reproducibility of data.": "",
  "A group of students measures the mass of a marble three times: Trial 1 = 5.2 g, Trial 2 = 5.3 g, Trial 3 = 5.1 g. Their teacher says the accepted mass is 5.2 g. Are their results accurate, precise, or both?": "",
  "Only accurate because the average matches the accepted value of 5.2 grams": "",
  "Only precise because the three measurements are very close to one another": "",
  "Both accurate and precise because the values are close to each other and to 5.2 g": "",
  "Neither accurate nor precise because none of the individual trials exactly equals 5.2 g": "",
  "The measurements are precise (they cluster tightly between 5.1 and 5.3 g) and accurate (their average of 5.2 g matches the accepted value). This is the ideal result in data collection.": ""
}